<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Diet &amp; Lifestyle Changes for Rectal Fissure Patients </h2>



<p>Diet and lifestyle changes can play a significant role in managing Rectal fissures. Here are some effective changes to consider: </p>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Dietary Changes for Rectal Fissures</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Increase Fiber Intake:</strong> Take fiber-containing foods such as fruits, complex carbohydrates, and vegetables and avoid straining the bowel.</li>



<li><strong>Stay Hydrated:</strong> Improve fluid intake by taking a lot of water regularly (8-10 glasses a day), so as to soften the stool.</li>



<li><strong>Avoid Spicy and Acidic Foods</strong>: Avoid spicy foods rich in oils, fatty foods or acidic foods in order to avoid further irritation.</li>



<li><strong>Include Healthy Fats</strong>: Include sources of healthy fats such as nuts, seeds and olive oil to particularly enhance bowel movement.</li>



<li><strong>Eat Smaller Meals</strong>: Eating small portions of food in between several times is better than eating massive amounts of food at once to alleviate the food digestion process in the stomach. </li>
</ul>



<h3 class="wp-block-heading">Lifestyle Changes for Rectal Fissures</h3>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Maintain Proper Hygiene:</strong> Wipe from front to back to avoid spreading bacteria around, and do not use soap to clean the anal area. Pat dry instead of rubbing.</li>



<li><strong>Avoid Prolonged Sitting:</strong> This is because pressure on the area is undesirable, and walking around or going off work can relieve pressure off that area.</li>



<li><strong>Exercise Regularly</strong>: Use a bathing suit, swim or walk or do some stretching exercises such as yoga to enhance digestion and blood circulation.</li>



<li><strong>Practice Regular Bowel Habits: </strong>Do not strain, and preferably go for a squat position while defecating.</li>



<li><strong>Reduce Stress:</strong> Deal with stress, especially by practising meditation or even respiratory, because stress can cause complications in digestion processes. </li>
</ul>



