<li><strong>Consume Vitamin C-Rich Foods:</strong> It can be taken from foods such as citrus, bell peppers, and kiwi as vitamin C is known to contain antioxidant properties that can restore the skin’s texture and decrease melanin production.</li>



<li><strong>Incorporate Omega-3 Fatty Acids:</strong> Avoid foods that are pro-inflammatory, such as meats, and consume foods with anti-inflammatory properties, such as fatty fish like salmon, chia seeds, and walnuts.</li>



<li><strong>Stay Hydrated: </strong>It is recommended that adults drink not less than eight glasses of water per day for the sake of skin and the whole body.</li>



<li><strong>Limit High-Carbohydrate Foods:</strong> Cuts down on the intake of refined carbohydrates and sugars that cause hormonal changes that cause melasma flare.</li>



<li><strong>Avoid Trigger Foods: </strong>Limit foods high in copper (including shellfish), soy foods, dairy products, and sweets that can make melasma worse.</li>



<li><strong>Include Folate-Rich Foods:</strong> It is recommended to take high amounts of foods with folic acid, including green leafy vegetables and whole grains because folate deficiency can lead to the formation of melasma.</li>



<li><strong>Opt for Colorful Vegetables:</strong> It also uses a number of brightly colored vegetables, such as carrots, and sweet potatoes, which are high in carotenoids to reduce the skin’s oxidative burden.</li>



<li><strong>Consider a Balanced Diet:</strong> It is advisable to take foods with low levels of saturated fats and refined sugar so that the skin may not produce the pigmentation referred to as melasma.</li>
</ul>



<h2 class="wp-block-heading">Lifestyle Changes for Melasma Patients</h2>



<ul class="wp-block-list">
<li><strong>Limit Sun Exposure:</strong> Wear sunscreen daily, hats, and protective clothing, and do not go outside between 10 a.m. and 4 p.m.</li>



